The 1921-22 season was Stoke's 29th season of league football and the fourth in the Second Division.

==Overview==
For the 1921-22 season [[Tom Brittleton]] was appointed as player-coach. It was Brittleton who would go on to find local talent such as [[Stanley Matthews]]. 

The season turned out to be one the best that the club had experienced for a long time and despite a 7-1 defeat to [[Hull City F.C.|Hull City]], promotion was gained to the top-flight, Stoke finishing as runners-up to Champions [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]. Eleven home draws cost Stoke the title but nevertheless their form the campaign was very good achieving a unbeaten run from the 27th December to the 8th of April.[[Jimmy Broad]] became top goalscorer with 25 goals to his name and also became the first Stoke player to score four goals in a Football League match achieving this feat in a 5-1 win over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in early December.

There were other highlights also. including a 4-2 win over local rivals [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] in the [[FA Cup]]. The match took place in front of 14,471 fans at [[Vale Park]] and gate receipts reached <U+00A3>1,138. Stoke progressed past [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] but [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] beat Stoke 4-0 in a 3rd round replay.

